<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-07-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-07-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="95" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 293.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-07-09"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 9, 1862.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of June 13, (No. 174,)
                            accompanied by Earl Russell’s final explanation on the case of the Emily
                            St. Pierre, has been received.</p>
                        <p>We have been unable here to find the parallel case in the diplomatic
                            correspondence referred to by you in connexion with this subject, and I
                            reserve further remarks upon this case until you shall have been able to
                            send it to us or direct our search for it.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>